  "original_title": "Sri Lanka acting president wants to review Easter bombings probe, may enlist UK help",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka acting president wants to review Easter bombings probe, may enlist UK help",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka\u2019s Acting President Ranil Wickremesinghe has called for a full-scale and impartial review of a probe into the 2019 Easter Sunday bombings that may see the government enlist the help of the UK police authorities.",
        "In a video statement released Monday July 18 afternoon, Wickremesinghe said investigations into the massacre was incomplete and he wished to have the matter resolved.",
        "\u201cThere is no need to drag it. There are other reports in addition to the commission\u2019s report. I would like to review it once more,\u201d he said.",
        "\u201cI think we must ensure that this is brought to an an end, and there should be a full-scale impartial review of the material that\u2019s available. If everyone is willing, I would like to get the help of the United Kingdom and their police authorities. They\u2019re the best we can find in addition to the people from Sri Lanka who will be working on this issue. It\u2019s the responsibility of the government to ensure that this matter is finalised without further delay,\u201d said Wickremesinghe.",
        "The Easter bombings, attributed to Islamist terrorists, killed 269 people and injured over 500. Former Defence Ministry Secretary Gotabaya Rajapkasa, widely regarded then as the national security candidate, won the November 2019 presidential election promising to carry out an impartial inquiry and punish those responsible.",
        "Widespread allegations of negligence were levelled at the then Yahapalana government of failing to act on early intelligence about the impending attack due to political infighting within the shaky ruling coalition of which Wickemesinghe was Prime Minister. A presidential commission of inquiry later recommended that criminal proceedings be instituted against former President Maithripala Sirisena and others over the incident. However, the commission cleared Wickremesinghe of any wrongdoing.",
        "The Rajapaksa years saw the issue become heavily politicised, with the head of Sri Lanka\u2019s Catholic Church Malcolm Cardinal Ranjith accusing the Rajapaksa government of using the attack to come into power.",
        "Following President Rajapaksa\u2019s resignation on July 14 after months of protest over his handling of Sri Lanka\u2019s economy, Wickremesinghe has been appointed acting president, with a parliamentary election due on Wednesday July 20 to elect a new interim president.",
        "Wickremesinghe is contesting for the position along with Opposition Leader Sajith Premadasa and two other candidates. (Colombo/Jul18/2022)"
      ],
